1
00:00:05,271 --> 00:00:10,081
Śrīla Guru Mahārāj,
one of his ontological themes

2
00:00:10,081 --> 00:00:16,813
is gradation of variety:
variety of tastes,

3
00:00:16,813 --> 00:00:19,353
variety of relationships,
everywhere.

4
00:00:19,680 --> 00:00:23,155
[Ultimate Celebration of Diversity]

5
00:00:23,556 --> 00:00:29,852
He would say sometimes,
“Equality? We hate it!”

6
00:00:30,579 --> 00:00:34,165
Once my sister in law said,
“Oh, like conservatives.”

7
00:00:34,165 --> 00:00:37,165
[Laughing]

8
00:00:37,165 --> 00:00:39,968
She liked that.

9
00:00:41,342 --> 00:00:47,189
And I’ve said a lot under the influence
of this type of thought,

10
00:00:47,189 --> 00:00:48,061
where he’s saying,

11
00:00:48,061 --> 00:00:52,511
“No two atoms are alike,
totally identical.

12
00:00:52,511 --> 00:00:55,054
Everything is unique.”

13
00:00:55,054 --> 00:00:59,017
So Americans,
they pride themselves

14
00:00:59,017 --> 00:01:04,201
on the wit and wisdom 
of Thomas Jefferson—

15
00:01:04,201 --> 00:01:11,261
a brilliant man, 
who Kennedy once said

16
00:01:11,261 --> 00:01:15,811
(they have an annual dinner at the Whitehouse
with all the journalists)

17
00:01:15,811 --> 00:01:20,940
and he said (he also had some wit)
and he said,

18
00:01:20,940 --> 00:01:24,503
looking at all these journalists
and brilliant people

19
00:01:24,503 --> 00:01:29,576
he said, “I think this is
the greatest assembly of intellect

20
00:01:29,576 --> 00:01:34,456
in the Whitehouse for a dinner,
with the exception perhaps

21
00:01:34,456 --> 00:01:40,466
of when Thomas Jefferson 
dined alone.” [Laughing]

22
00:01:40,468 --> 00:01:48,102
So that man—Declaration of Independence,
other things …

23
00:01:48,455 --> 00:01:52,643
It begins with,
“All men are created equal.”

24
00:01:52,643 --> 00:01:58,308
So they like to say that
“Yes, that’s the promise that is America,

25
00:01:58,308 --> 00:02:01,160
all men 
are created equal.”

26
00:02:01,160 --> 00:02:07,023
But a faulty statement— 
it did not include women,

27
00:02:07,023 --> 00:02:12,884
nor people of colour and 
other types of living beings.

28
00:02:12,884 --> 00:02:24,800
So, not one to be known
for a lack of audacity.

29
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:31,500
I like to restate that as,
to be more inclusive,

30
00:02:31,500 --> 00:02:35,941
that all beings 
are eternally unique.

31
00:02:37,927 --> 00:02:39,997
This is a beautiful thing.

32
00:02:39,997 --> 00:02:41,942
Like the French
have the saying,

33
00:02:41,942 --> 00:02:45,377
“Vive le difference.”

34
00:02:45,546 --> 00:02:50,398
The differences between us
sometimes bring us into conflict,

35
00:02:50,398 --> 00:02:54,052
but from another point of view, 
are to be celebrated.

36
00:02:54,052 --> 00:02:57,924
The individuality,
the uniqueness.

37
00:03:00,377 --> 00:03:05,299
I tried to remind people in China recently, 
and elsewhere, that

38
00:03:05,299 --> 00:03:09,366
“You are eternally
unique individuals.”

39
00:03:09,366 --> 00:03:09,846
When we say,

40
00:03:09,846 --> 00:03:12,180
“Jīvera ‘svarūpa’ haya—
Kṛṣṇera ‘nitya-dāsa’” [Cc: 2.20.108-109]

41
00:03:12,180 --> 00:03:15,499
That is the meaning:
you have a unique identity.

42
00:03:16,102 --> 00:03:20,173
There aren’t two of you.
Right?

43
00:03:20,173 --> 00:03:28,058
Even when there are identical twins,
they’re different.

44
00:03:29,720 --> 00:03:33,944
Superficially they’re the same, 
but internally different.

45
00:03:33,944 --> 00:03:36,720
I was sitting next to a lady
on the airplane once

46
00:03:36,720 --> 00:03:41,457
and she had two little girls, 
her daughters, twins,

47
00:03:41,457 --> 00:03:45,354
and they looked like 
they were three or four years old.

48
00:03:46,884 --> 00:03:51,655
And she said, 
“This one is like a girly-girl,”

49
00:03:51,655 --> 00:03:52,922
(they’re dressed identically)

50
00:03:52,922 --> 00:03:56,652
“she’s very feminine 
and delicate, her movements …”

51
00:03:56,652 --> 00:03:59,803
she said,
“This one, like a tom-boy.”

52
00:03:59,895 --> 00:04:05,403
They looked identical but
their personalities are different,

53
00:04:05,403 --> 00:04:07,525
unique.

54
00:04:08,587 --> 00:04:13,870
So when I heard 
the world’s leading authority on Hinduism

55
00:04:13,870 --> 00:04:16,814
speaks at the University of California,
Los Angeles,

56
00:04:16,814 --> 00:04:20,649
A. L. Basham,
he wrote a famous book called

57
00:04:20,649 --> 00:04:24,283
“The Wonder that was India” …

58
00:04:25,191 --> 00:04:32,737
So, pre-wikipedia, pre-internet, 
when there was the encyclopedia,

59
00:04:32,768 --> 00:04:39,203
he would write the entry 
for Hinduism and other things.

60
00:04:40,410 --> 00:04:43,678
And in his talk 
he discussed many things,

61
00:04:43,678 --> 00:04:47,140
but you could tell he was—
I consider him and as others do—

62
00:04:47,140 --> 00:04:56,403
a closet Kṛṣṇa-ite that shows
many natural predispositions

63
00:04:56,403 --> 00:05:00,237
towards Kṛṣṇa conception, 
and Viṣṇu-bhakti,

64
00:05:00,237 --> 00:05:05,653
and just the whole, 
what is the wonder that is India.

65
00:05:05,653 --> 00:05:10,128
When it came to māyāvād, 
you could argue,

66
00:05:10,128 --> 00:05:14,312
“The Śaṅkara-ites vs the Vaiṣṇava-ites 
and Mādhava and Rāmānuja …”,

67
00:05:14,312 --> 00:05:17,125
but he put it very nicely, 
at one point,

68
00:05:17,125 --> 00:05:19,856
on the idea 
that we’re all one.

69
00:05:19,856 --> 00:05:25,146
He said,
“I don’t know if I want to be you.”

70
00:05:25,146 --> 00:05:27,506
[Laughing]

71
00:05:27,506 --> 00:05:29,336
Finished.

72
00:05:29,336 --> 00:05:31,856
He said it so, like, ‘euch’.

73
00:05:31,856 --> 00:05:35,236
[Laughing]

74
00:05:35,236 --> 00:05:39,046
So he dismissed māyāvād 
in one little statement:

75
00:05:39,046 --> 00:05:43,796
“I don’t know if I want to be you.”
Right?

76
00:05:44,524 --> 00:05:52,593
So, Kṛṣṇa consciousness is 
the ultimate celebration of diversity.

77
00:05:52,593 --> 00:05:56,868
Really. To the extreme.

